ISO-human-mind-language
senso-concept-Mcs (lagoIsox)

McsHitp-creation:: {2021-05-30},

overview of lagoHmnm

description::
"ISO 639 is a set of standards by the International Organization for Standardization that is concerned with representation of names for languages and language groups.
It was also the name of the original standard, approved in 1967 (as ISO 639/R)[1] and withdrawn in 2002.[2] The ISO 639 set consists of five parts."
[{2021-05-30 retrieved} https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_639]

lagoHmnm.ISO.639-3m-0012

description::
"Some existing code elements in ISO 639-2, and the corresponding code elements in ISO 639-1, are designated in those parts of ISO 639 as individual language code elements, yet are in a one-to-many relationship with individual language code elements in [ISO 639-3]. For purposes of [ISO 639-3], they are considered to be macrolanguage code elements.
— ISO 639-3: Relationship between ISO 639-3 and the other parts of ISO 639[2]"
[{2020-11-23} https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_639_macrolanguage]

name::
* McsEngl.ISO.639-3m!⇒lagoIso3m,
* McsEngl.lagoHmnm.0012-ISO.639-3m!⇒lagoIso3m,
* McsEngl.lagoHmnm.ISO.639-3m!⇒lagoIso3m,
* McsEngl.lagoIso3m,

lagoHmnm.ISO.639-5

description::
ISO 639-5: This part clearly indicates the ISO 639-5 standard. ISO 639-5 is part of the ISO 639 series of international standards. Specifically, ISO 639-5 deals with language families and groups. It provides codes for collections of languages that share a common origin or are geographically or typologically related, but are not considered individual languages in themselves (which are covered by ISO 639-1, -2, -3).

name::
* McsEngl.ISO.639-5!⇒lagoIso5,
* McsEngl.lagoHmnm.0013-ISO.639-5!⇒lagoIso5,
* McsEngl.lagoHmnm.ISO.639-5!⇒lagoIso5,
* McsEngl.lagoIso5,
